I wouldn&#39;t try to go as far as detecting devices. The better idea is to look for support.
In this case you want to know if the device supports a pointer device and is capable of hover. If not capable of hover then at least it should support touch. With touch you can still access the focus states.

**HTML**

    &lt;div class=&quot;row&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;td&quot;&gt;
            &lt;a class=&quot;btn btn-primary&quot; title=&quot;buy&quot;&gt;
                &lt;i class=&quot;fa fa-shopping-cart&quot; aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;
                &lt;span&gt;Add to shopping cart&lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/a&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

**CSS**

    .row .btn span { display: none; } // mobile first don&#39;t display the button text
    .row .btn .fa { display: inline-block; } // mobile first display icon

    @media (any-hover: hover) {
        .row .btn span { display: inline-block; }
        .row .btn .fa { display: none; }
        .row .btn:hover .fa,
        .row .btn:active .fa,
        .row .btn:focus .fa { display: inline-block; }
    }

Haven&#39;t tested this code, but this is how I would start working on a solution.

